For me, that was a risk/return worth taking given battery day had at least a chance of being an explosive upside catalyst. I still think there will be some upgrades coming in for $TSLA tomorrow morning so could still be a situation where I make more on the upside of this trade.

In that scenario I outlined, just as an example, if $TSLA rallied to $514 by Friday, I would have made a gain of $150/sh. As the trade is playing out, with $TSLA sub-400, I will make a minimum profit on this trade of $59.76/sh regardless of how low $TSLA goes.

2. I have a September 25th 500 call from $6.24 that will be essentially worthless at $TSLA's current share price, hence a loss of $6.24/sh.
3. I am short an October 16th 500 call from $50 that will likely be something like $5 at TSLA's current share price, netting $45/sh.

The net takeaway is this:
1. I have 100 shares from a cost basis of $364/sh and a 400 put contract at a cost of $15, regardless of where $TSLA stock trades this week, I will be able to close this position for a minimum of $385/sh, thus securing $21/sh in profit, again, minimum.

No matter how low $TSLA goes, I will be insured at an effective price of $385/sh. And for the previous scenario where it rallied to 514, I would have sacrificed the $15/sh on this put as an insurance premium payment, so the upside scenario would have ended up netting $150/sh.

Lets say $TSLA rallied to $514 by Friday. I'd be up $150/sh, and closing the October call partially using proceeds from selling the weekly 500 call would have netted $15 to $20/sh. The net gain in that scenario would be around $165/sh.
Thus, if $TSLA rallied over $500, I should have been able to sell the weekly call and use those gains to buy-to-close the October 500 call for a net cost somewhere in the $30 to $35 range.

In the event I was wrong to the upside, and $TSLA rallied through 500, I could effectively uncap my gains by buying this call. If $TSLA traded over $500, the inherent value of the weekly contract would be increasing at a rate similar to the value of the short October call.

As it traded up to 460 on 9/15, I had a choice to make:
1. Sell for a gain of $96/sh
2. Let the position ride hoping $TSLA went higher
3. Sell a covered call, lock in more upside, but cap the maximum possible gain on the trade
